## Plan: Add Pagination to `GET /users`

### What I found

The codebase is a TypeScript Express API with:
- **`src/routes.ts`** — the only file that needs changing (currently `res.json(users)` returns all 15 users flat)
- **`src/data.ts`** — 15 in-memory `User` objects
- **`tests/routes.test.ts`** — test suite already written and waiting for the feature

### The single change: `src/routes.ts`

Replace the current 3-line handler with:

```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;
  const total = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data  = users.slice(start, start + limit);   // naturally [] when out-of-range

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

### Why each test passes

| Test | `page` | `limit` | `data.length` | `totalPages` |
|------|--------|---------|---------------|--------------|
| Default | 1 | 10 | 10 | 2 |
| Page 2 | 2 | 10 | 5 | 2 |
| Custom limit | 1 | 5 | 5 | 3 |
| Out-of-range | 100 | 10 | **0** (`[]`) | 2 |

`Array.slice()` with a start index past the end returns `[]` natively — no special-case needed for out-of-range pages. `GET /users/:id` is completely untouched.

